The paper focuses on the use of deep convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for visual instance retrieval, which is a subfield of computer vision and information retrieval. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also evaluates the effectiveness of different factors that impact the discriminative ability of features extracted from CNNs, which falls under the category of machine learning. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a new multi-scale image feature representation method, which involves image processing and computer graphics, making cs.MM (Multimedia) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper aims to achieve state-of-the-art performance on visual instance retrieval datasets, which is a common goal in the field of artificial intelligence. Therefore, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a possible sub-category.
